snippet.textDisplay: Let's face it, folks. America is the most diverse it's ever been, and even though some may disagree about the "appropriateness" of that halftime show, we must realize that, because the Bowl was in Miami, the entertainment portion of the night had to reflect and represent that location, that culture, as was the case in Atlanta last year. That being said, I just have a problem with the fact that so much was made of Janet Jackson's UNINTENTIONAL "wardrobe malfunction" 16 years ago, to the point where her career was almost unfairly destroyed, and she has never been invited back to perform. I'm sure millions would be thrilled to see THAT halftime show, including me!

snippet.textDisplay:
Good Job Marie for stating a realistic opinion and understanding the perspective of a parent who is trying to teach their kids to be respectful and modest. I'm Latina and am very passionate about my culture and other cultures. And as a performer myself, there is a way to represent your culture without being half naked and so sexual.
I used to love JLo and Shakira and I still do, but I think its shameful that they need to fall into the Hollywood unrealistic standard of having to expose their bodies and dance as if there are no children present. These are very strong and influential Latinas who I grew up watching and had a lot of respect for because they were so different from the stereo typical celebrity. They both are SUPER talented they dont need to do all that for me or many others to watch them. And that goes for both men and and women performers.
What happened to teaching boys to respect women? And what happened to teaching girls that beauty comes from within? How can we teach them that if we dont exemplify that?
So thank you Marie for not going with the crowd on that one and not being afraid to express your concern, which is actually the same concern many parents with children have. I wished you could have expressed yourself more without being ridiculed by the others at the table.
